04248nam a22005415i 9780226723358DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102010ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802267233587 a10.7208/97802267233582doi  a(DE-B1597)524059  a(OCoLC)642685760  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQD248b.R63 2010eb 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a540.9/0342221 aRocke, Alan J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImage and Reality :bKekulé, Kopp, and the Scientific Imagination /cAlan J. Rocke. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (416 p.) :b44 halftones, 3 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSynthesis00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- t1. Ether/Or -- t2. The Architect of Molecules -- t3. Building an Unseen Structure -- t4. A Barometer of the Science -- t5. The Heuristics of Molecular Representation -- t6. Molecules as Metaphors -- t7. Aromatic Apparitions -- t8. Dimensional Molecules -- t9. Kopp’s World -- t10. Kekulé’s “Dreams” -- t11. The Scientific Image-ination -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNineteenth-century chemists were faced with a particular problem: how to depict the atoms and molecules that are beyond the direct reach of our bodily senses. In visualizing this microworld, these scientists were the first to move beyond high-level philosophical speculations regarding the unseen. In Image and Reality, Alan Rocke focuses on the community of organic chemists in Germany to provide the basis for a fuller understanding of the nature of scientific creativity. Arguing that visual mental images regularly assisted many of these scientists in thinking through old problems and new possibilities, Rocke uses a variety of sources, including private correspondence, diagrams and illustrations, scientific papers, and public statements, to investigate their ability to not only imagine the invisibly tiny atoms and molecules upon which they operated daily, but to build detailed and empirically based pictures of how all of the atoms in complicated molecules were interconnected. These portrayals of “chemical structures,” both as mental images and as paper tools, gradually became an accepted part of science during these years and are now regarded as one of the central defining features of chemistry. In telling this fascinating story in a manner accessible to the lay reader, Rocke also suggests that imagistic thinking is often at the heart of creative thinking in all fields. Image and Reality is the first book in the Synthesis series, a series in the history of chemistry, broadly construed, edited by Angela N. H. Creager, John E. Lesch, Stuart W. Leslie, Lawrence M. Principe, Alan Rocke, E.C. Spary, and Audra J. Wolfe, in partnership with the Chemical Heritage Foundation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChemistry, OrganicxHistoryy19th century. 0aImagination. 0aSciencexMethodologyxHistory. 0aVisualization. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226723358423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226723358.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles